Tesla Models¶

quick summary

  • Tesla cars bring together several controversies about the use of safety and quality of cars. Among them, the Tesla Model S that braked sharply in the tunnel and caused a traffic jam,another was the Tesla Model 3 that invaded a building at more than 100km/h, the occurrence of accidents involving the automation of vehicles, in which the autopilot is activated, as a result of this, factors such as the AutoPilot shutdown before an accident happens , software failures and even human recklessness and precipitation, end up causing accidents with dead or injured people. Recently, the Tesla Model Y had a software failure and caused an accident leaving two dead and three injured in China.

  • The dataset gathers details about accidents involving pedestrians, cyclists, other vehicles and alleged failures. Here I present my simplified analysis of the available data.

df.columns = df.columns.str.replace(' ','')
In [6]:
# Select columns with numeric data
columns = ['Tesladriver', 'Teslaoccupant', 'Othervehicle', 'Cyclists/Peds',
           'TSLA+cycl/peds', 'AutoPilotclaimed', 'VerifiedTeslaAutopilotDeath']
numeric_df = df[columns]

# Remove NaN values from selected columns
numeric_df = numeric_df.dropna()

# Replace selected columns in original DataFrame
df[columns] = numeric_df

# Remove selected columns
df.drop(['Note', 'Deceased3', 'Deceased4'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Replace specific values with 'Unknown' or '0'
df[['Deceased1', 'Deceased2', 'Model', 'State', 'Country']] = df[['Deceased1', 'Deceased2', 'Model', 'State', 'Country']].replace([' - ', ' '], 'Unknown').fillna('Unknown')
df[['Tesladriver', 'Teslaoccupant', 'Othervehicle', 'Cyclists/Peds', 'TSLA+cycl/peds', 'AutoPilotclaimed', 'VerifiedTeslaAutopilotDeath']] = df[['Tesladriver', 'Teslaoccupant', 'Othervehicle', 'Cyclists/Peds', 'TSLA+cycl/peds', 'AutoPilotclaimed', 'VerifiedTeslaAutopilotDeath']].replace(' - ', 'Unknown').fillna('0')

# Replace missing data in the 'Model' column with 'model not added'
df['Model'] = df['Model'].fillna('model not added')

# Convert 'Date' column to datetime and create new columns for month and day of week
df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'])
df['Date Month'] = df['Date'].dt.strftime('%b')
df['Date Week'] = df['Date'].dt.strftime('%A')
df['Year'] = df['Date'].dt.year

number of accidents involving cyclists and pedestrians per year¶

In [67]:
# Get count of occurrences of each unique value in the 'Country' column
columns = df['Country'].value_counts()

# Create a figure with subplots for each unique country
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=len(columns), ncols=1, figsize=(10, len(columns)*5))

# Iterate over each unique country
for i, (country, data) in enumerate(df.groupby('Country')):
    # Create a countplot of the distribution of the 'Cyclists/Peds' variable over the 'Year' variable
    sns.countplot(x='Year', hue='Cyclists/Peds', data=data, palette='Set2', ax=axes[i])
    # Set the title of the subplot to the name of the country
    axes[i].set_title(country, fontweight='bold')
    # Add labels to the bars in the countplot
    for j in axes[i].containers:
        axes[i].bar_label(j, fontsize=12)
    # Add a legend to the subplot
    axes[i].legend(loc='upper right')
    
# Add a main title to the figure
fig.suptitle('Distribution of Cyclists/Peds over Year by Country', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
# Adjust the spacing between the subplots to avoid overlapping
fig.tight_layout(pad=3.0)
# Show the figure
plt.show()

number of deaths per year in each country¶

In [73]:
columns = df['Country'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 90))

for i, col in enumerate(columns.index):
    fig = plt.subplot(22, 2, i+1)
    sns.countplot(x='Deaths', data=df[df['Country'] == col], palette='Set2')
    plt.title(col, fontweight='bold', fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
    for container in fig.containers:
        fig.bar_label(container)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

number of deaths per year¶

In [74]:
columns = df['Country'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 90))

for i, col in enumerate(columns.index):
    fig = plt.subplot(22, 2, i+1)
    sns.countplot(x='Year', hue='Deaths', data=df[df['Country'] == col], palette='Set2')
    plt.title(col, fontweight='bold', fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=13)
    plt.xlabel('')
    for container in fig.containers:
        fig.bar_label(container, fontsize=14)
    plt.legend(loc=2, bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1))

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
